metadata.name: fx(mash) #143
metadata.description:
fx(mash) is my humble contribution to celebrating #fxhashturnsone

This series is based on a simple algorithm - lines of a random length are drawn on a square grid until the grid is full.

I have added a variety of features based on some of my favorite fxhash projects and a few special guests.

This collection is intentionally diverse and disorderly, that's a nice way of saying I only had a short period of time following the release of Acequia. As a result, some of the outputs might be weird, messy, or even bordering on broken (if you get one of the latter please let me know and I'll reimburse you).

Despite being a bit rough around the edges, I hope fx(mash) reflects some measure of my love for the fxhash community. If you're feeling kind, then perhaps it even harks back to the experimental early days :)

The last year has been an incredible journey, thank you for letting me be a part of our story so far.

Controls (in live view):

- Press [s] to save the current image
- Press [g] to toggle grain
- Press [h] for a high-res output

Beta Controls (in live view, definitely not fully tested):

- Press [p] to start/pause animation
- Press [i] to slow down animation
- Press [o] to speed up animation

All primary sales go to Savepakistan.


Acknowledgements:

fx(mash) uses Gorilla Sun's grain implementation, a big thanks to him and meezwhite for a great article that is well worth supporting https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/all-about-that-grain

metadata.name: Hexagones Landscape #354
metadata.description:
An undulating (sometimes) landscape made up of hexagons (or "Hexagones" laying in wait) to celebrate the first birthday of fxhash. Written at the last minute the weekend before the birthday week.

A simpler 16 colour version of this project was originally coded on an Atari ST 512, about 32 years ago, figured it was time to update it.

INSTRUCTIONS ::

h - Toggle high-res
s - Download and save image

PRINTING INSTRUCTIONS ::

High-res will output a 6,553 x 8,192 image, at 300dpi it should print at...

21.84 x 27.3 inches
55.47 x 69.3 cm

metadata.name: Antilepton Factory #5
metadata.description:
A quasi-simulation exploring variations of the antimatter content of a primitive universe,
1 048 576 particles are subjected to the fluctuations of a digital scalar force field.

Each one of the 60 frames per second is a unique generative composition.

(Click ‘open’ to see fullscreen, use wheel/pinch to zoom micro/macro )

-----
* Mint preview *

Minter will get a loopless determinist animation, and a 4320x4320 PNG bitmap.
The "cover" iteration featured here by default uses a 10seconds animation cycle, but new mints will have random animation mode cycles lasting between 1 and 60 seconds. 
To enable the "regular perturbation" mode (10s cycles) please see below "URL modifiers".

-----
* Technics *

This experience is designed to be executed on a recent GPU (>2016) and displayed on 16/9 screens from FHD to 8K+ (1920x1080 → 7680x4320) at 60FPS for infinite duration as the animation scales and creates never-before-seen patterns.

- JavaScript / ThreeJS / WebGL
- Unique generative and determinist animation (animation is seeded by the fxhash mint hash)
- Unlimited duration (no loop) / 6 animations
- 1 second to 1 minute internal algorithm variations

-----
* Controls *

Wheel/pinch : zoom in/out to observe the phenomenon on different scales
Right click + drag : move the observation area
Key "Space" : take a PNG capture of the current view frame (same ratio as window, max 1920x1080)

-----
* URL modifiers *

"&scalartemperature=1400" 
displays the animation with another color.
Colors are expressed in terms of blackbody radiation at a given temperature. Here it will be 1400 Kelvin degrees (~1120°C / 2060°F) corresponding to a lightly hotter than red particles. 
Values accepted in the range 800K to 1 000 000K.

"&perturbation=regular"
allows a regular cycle of animations, each animation mode will be active for 10 seconds

-----
@HAL09999 – November 2022

metadata.name: Rondelle, Listen #69
metadata.description:
Tap to start sound. Tap to mute.

Inspired by the glass rondelles which hung from the windowsill in my childhood home. I ask myself what would these rondelles sound like if they reflected sound instead of light? To me, I hear hopeful harmonies of memories past, but they are falling in and out of tune and they are occluded by the muffled noise of time.

When a rondelle is minted, a transaction hash is injected into its code. All colors, patterns, sounds, and motions are generated deterministically from this transaction hash.

As the rondelle loads in your browser, a real-time generative algorithm writes tones, noise, feedback, and distortion to three looping audio buffers. During playback, oscillations in pan, pitch, and volume track the visual oscillations among the rondelle's color rings.

Rarity features are included. The least common rondelles are closed center, monochrome, smol, split color, and square.

Made with Web Audio and p5js. Minted on fxhash beta. Idlebit, 2021.

metadata.name: RADICAL #41
Plottable Mountain Moons #216
metadata.description:
What makes this NFT have value? not only the digital is cool but it is the recipe to a plottable. Owning this NFT confers the right to request a physical plot (21cm square). @greweb will ask extra fees for this service => https://greweb.me/plots/nft

Full article: https://greweb.me/2021/12/plottable-mountain-moons

Plottable Mountain Moons generalize many explorations done this year. There are 13 inks, 9 different shape primitives with recursion, various intensity, and frequencies of noise,... and many rare cases to discover!

Digital and Physical art, hybrid and decoupled:
- The art is published via a digital NFT on Tezos blockchain – its digital representation simulates fountain pen inks drawing on paper with animated effects.
- Token to the physical world: owning each NFT confer the power to request the related physical plot: https://greweb.me/plots/nft

@greweb – 2021 – tech: WebGL + Rust + WASM – CC BY-SA 4.0 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/4.0/

metadata.name: Siena #93
metadata.description:
Siena is a generative piece creating trails made with Javascript.
This piece is based on researches of an upcoming piece called RIO.
Algorithm written in Siena, Italia by Quentin Hocdé - 15/11/2021.
Each token have a unique color theme, and each square's size and positions are generated.

metadata.name: ASCII Squigl 2 #40
metadata.description:
fx({asciiSquigl:'Bigger and better Squigls flowing through the Tezos Blockchain.'})

ASCII Squigl 2 has 13 attributes and they are drawn to a 1000 x 1000 px canvas with a density of 4 (4000 x 4000 px on save).

- Size of grid
- Light, Dark, Rainbow, Grayscale or Blue and White console
- Main color
- Character mode
- Amount of characters in Squigl
- Characters used in Squigl
- Amount of characters in Background
- Characters used in Background
- Animation type
- Animation speed
- Pattern type
- Color reverse (Boolean)
- Bugged pattern (Boolean)

Save image with 's'
Stop animation with mouseclick

Font: MxPlus IBM EGA 8x8 / VileR (CC BY-SA 4.0)

Made with P5JS and shaky hands.

LFG Squiglmaniacs <3 / hic et squigl 2022

metadata.name: Punktwelt #386
metadata.description:
Continuing on the theme of color perception in Farbteiler, Punktwelt is an exploration of color interaction, projection and perceived depth, and the aesthetics of simple Boolean operations on form.

Each shape is the result of a single block, a rectangular cuboid, subjected to a series of Boolean subtractions with other blocks, and rendered in parallel projection, oblique or axonometric, in the abstract landscape of the Punktwelt.

Some have horizons, some have banded or striped backgrounds. The unnatural drawing order and chromatic differences of the individual faces sometimes yields illusory or paradoxical visual geometries.

Press ’s’ to save a png. Press ’4’ to export a high resolution png. Press ’8’ to export a very high resolution png. Press ’e’ to export an SVG file (may take some time and produce large files).

Aspect ratio variations are 4:5, 5:4, 2:3, 3:2 and 1:1.

Built in Javascript with p5.js, p5.svg and csg.js.

metadata.name: Dreamcatcher Forest #524
metadata.description:
"Dreamcatcher Forest" is part of the fxhash interactive minting experience at Art Basel, Basel 2022. The illustration in this work draws inspiration from Native American dreamcatchers, a protective talisman crafted from beautifully intricate patterns of woven thread, built from natural materials & colorful beads.

Dreamcatchers are used to protect dreamers while they sleep. Good dreams are able to slip through the web to meet the sleeper beneath, while bad dreams are trapped and prevented.

- Use the "S" key to save a PNG image.
- Use the "P" key to export a print-quality image.

metadata.name: Coronado #130
metadata.description:
This series is about the beauty and charm of imperfection, chaos amidst order, and letting go. It's about knowing that however much control we think we may have, things can all fall apart or burst into something unexpectedly wonderful at any moment, even without our hands tightly on the reigns.

Please see fxtext article linked from main project page for more background on the project and rendering notes.

Some key commands in live mode:

G : Toggle grain
S : Save current resolution
1 : 4000x5000
2 : 6000x7500
3 : 8000x10000
4 : 10000x12500
5 : 12000x15000
6 : 14000x17500
(1-6 work best on Chrome)
(rendering takes longer as resolution increases)
